  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - MAGICIAN</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>FAST LVLS EASILY 1-7!! PLUS CHARACTER CREATION!!</font> - <small>Yadien, Saryrn</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><p>
<br>
Ahh a mage, yes you have picked a good class. But one of the
hardest levels for me as a mage was lvl 3. Simply becuase I did
not know what to fight. Also you dont have any pets before lvl 4.
Plus all levels before your next spell levels will be very very
bad. But don't worry I will tell you how to get through it! It
actually is quite simple. First off when creating a mage is what
race. There are quite a few races, let me name some<br>
<br>
Human - Generally not a good choice, IMHO. Two reasons, one there
INT is the lowest of all, which can be made up for at higher
levels, but it does cost a bit of money you could have used
elsewhere. Second is no nightvision, which is not good and if you
haven't ever seen the land you will be hunting in earlier, you
could easily get lost and die and never find your corpse.<br>
<br>
High-Elf - This was my choice, it has pretty good INT and well
balenced stats otherwise, and I did like the starting area, which
is a plus. Also has a little infravision I believe.<br>
<br>
Erudite - Highest INT of all classes, good choice. They also have
very poor eyesight in the night like the humans. Plus they have
to take a boat to qeynos for better hunting later on.<br>
<br>
Gnome - They have excellent INT. They also have very high DEX and
AGI. Plus they are small so they look cool ;) They have the
tinkering ability also. And they can see in the dark which is
very good.<br>
<br>
Dark Elf - Last but not least. Had second highest INT.
Ultravision which just rocks! Heh trust me when it gets dark out
it is harder to hunt which in return can lead to less exp during
the night. One problem, I probably would have chosen this class,
if they were not evil. The one problem with being evil is fewer
places to hunt, and the amounts of walking and travel to go to
the bank or to get your spells if far away from your hometown.
Also not being able to buy from vendors is not good either.<br>
<br>
<br>
Well ok now that you have picked your race it<br>
is time to pick your bonus stats. For me on all races I would put
as much into INT as I can, and if I have anything left over I
would put it into AGI. Now create your character!<br>
<br>
Ok now that you are in the game it is time to equip your dagger
and take your note to your guildmaster. I would suggest you just
look around the town for your guild so you get to know the town
better. Ok now that you have your tunic, put it on and go out
into your newbie garden and start to kill stuff. Make sure you
con it first and it has to be White or Blue or Black before you
attack it!! If not don't! Don't attack yellow or reds, you will
die. Also do not make the mistake my friend has been doing and
dont worry about tailoring or quests or anything else at least
untill lvl 6. The reason? Well my friend has spent hours doing
this one quest to get an ac3 shield hehe. It is not smart. He
could have gotten to lvl 5 easily in the hours he has spent doing
that quest. Now once you reach lvl 2 only attack blues, and if
you have full health and full mana then attack a yellow. This is
becuase of downtime, (Sitting down resting for mana and health)
If you attack whites you will get hurt more and waste more mana,
so you have to sit down longer. If you attack blues you should
have little to no downtime. Now once you get to level 3 you are
just 1 level away from PETS!!! Here is the key attack lvl 1s and
lvl 2s ONLY. Do NOT leave your newbie garden. Go from monster to
monster, don't stop to read auctions DO NOT GROUP! Do not stop to
go to town for quests, just kill kill kill. Trust me doing this
you could probably get from lvl 1-4 in 2 hours. I have done it,
also loot everything untill lvl 3. Then you should have enough
stuff to buy your pet spell. Buy that first. If you do not have
enough money you can kill decaying skeletons for bone chips and
sell a stack for 3pp. Now at lvl 4 go out further into you newbie
area. Orc hill for High Elves. East commons for Humans. Qeynos
Hills for Erudites, and Humans. And further into Nek forest for
dark elves. For gnomes I have never been to there area so I do
not know. If you are a gnome just tavel further ahead and away
from your city, but not too far. Now you should just keep conning
stuff and hunting whites,blacks,blues and if you are pretty good
you can hunt yellows. Keep doing this from 4-7 and the exp should
just roll in.<br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
</td></tr>
